\begin_layout Subsection
Risk Sharing in Labour Markets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The particular case we're concerned with is that in labour markets.
 Given that rural sector is the key employer in the developing countries
 and the natural of rural employment is quite labour-intensive, an analysis
 of agricultural labour market covers a significant part of economy.
 In terms of the Lewis-Rani-Fei model, the process of urbanization itself
 is tied with the development of labour market in the development countries.
 Hence, risks in the labour market can affect the wages in the rural sector
 (if workers take a lot of risk then their productivity is affected - whereas
 if employers take a lot of risk, then the labour wages are lowered).
 The decline in wages of rural sector might as well be in interest of the
 urban sector (see notes on the political conflicts resulting from taxation
 and subsidies-related pressures on the government).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Imperfect Networks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consumption smoothing is an important motivation for gifts and informal
 loans, but gifts and loans are unable to efficiently share risk at the
 village level (gifts and loans take place not at the village level but
 within closed networks).
 Informal loans charge no interest; mutual insurance is largely confined
 to networks; and not all shocks are insured.
 Risk sharing takes place through repeated informal transactions based on
 reciprocity and mutual insurance takes place through a mix of gifts and
 no interest loans
