\begin_layout Subsection
Moral Hazard
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a clear problem is a farmer/participant doesn't want to put a lot
 of effort is s/he sees a certain income is guaranteed as the lower output
 performer (free-riding on high-output farmers).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If high efforts are with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and no efforts with 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, then expected utility with high efforts is 
\begin_inset Formula $pU(H)+(1-p)U(L)-c$
\end_inset

 while no efforts yield 
\begin_inset Formula $qU(H)+(1-q)U(L)$
\end_inset

.
 Without insurance, the farmer puts extra effort if 
\begin_inset Formula $pU(H)+(1-p)U(L)-c>qU(H)+(1-q)U(L)$
\end_inset

.
 With insurance, if farmers with H pool their harvests and with L receive
 a compensation, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $pH+(1-p)L$
\end_inset

 assured for every farmer and since, 
\begin_inset Formula $U(pH+(1-p)L)>pU(H)+(1-p)U(L)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question that one may ask is how much insurance can be offered without
 worsening incentives? If perfect insurance conditions fails to hold we
 consider the second best-alternative.
 
\begin_inset Formula $pX+(1-p)Y=pH+(1-p)L$
\end_inset

 for farmer's output 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 High efforts are chosen as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $pU(X)+(1-p)U(Y)-C\ge qU(X)+(1-q)U(Y)\Rightarrow(p-q)(U(X)-U(Y))\Rightarrow C$
\end_inset

.
 Under the second best scheme, individual consumption must move with individual
 income.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering, the reliability of a mutual insurance scheme, let us consider
 the gain from a high output individual who breaks the contract 
\begin_inset Formula $G=U(H)-U(M)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $M=pH+(1-p)L).$
\end_inset

 The enforcement constraint would require that loss be higher than gain.
 So to not break the contract we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $L>G$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U(H)-U(M)\le N[U(M)-\{pU(H)+(1-p)U(L)\}]+S$
\end_inset

 (social sanctions = 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

).
 This implies that large
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L-H$
\end_inset

 would encourage breaking of contract.
 If the possibility for self-insurance exists, then mutual insurance is
 likely to fail.
\end_layout

